<para xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="3" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2.s1">
The zeros in Table 36.7.1 are points in the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2.m1">\mathbf{x}=(x,y)</Math> plane, where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2.m2">\operatorname{ph}\Psi_{2}\left(\mathbf{x}\right)</Math> is undetermined. All zeros have <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2.m3">y&lt;0</Math> , and fall into two classes.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2.s2">
Inside the cusp, that is, for <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2.m4">x^{2}&lt;8|y|^{3}/27</Math> , the zeros form pairs lying in curved rows.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="3" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2.s3">
Close to the <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C36.S7.SS2.p2.m5">y</Math> -axis the approximate location of these zeros is given by <Math equation-number="36.7.1" mode="display" xml:id="C36.S7.E1">y_{m}=-\sqrt{2\pi(2m+1)}, if m=1,2,3,\dots, //// x_{m,n}^{\pm}=\sqrt{\dfrac{2}{-y_{m}}}\left(2n+\tfrac{1}{2}+(-1)^{m}\tfrac{1}{ 2}\pm\tfrac{1}{4}\right)\pi, if m=1,2,3,\dots, n=0,\pm 1,\pm 2,\dots</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
          
